on and aspectual structure -- tReal adjuncts in the Instrumental in Russian -- tGerman participle II constructions as adjuncts -- tSubject index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnlike the notion of "argument" that is central to modern linguistic theorizing, the phenomena that are commonly subsumed under the complementary notion "adjunct" so far have not attracted the attention they deserve. In this volume, leading experts in the field present current approaches to the grammar and pragmatics of adjuncts. The contributions scrutinize i.a. the argument-adjunct distinction, specify conditions of adjunct placement, discuss compositionality issues, and propose new analyses of event-related modification. They are meant to shed new light on an area of linguistic structure that is deemed to be notoriously overlooked.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxAdjuncts. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 4aAdjunkt ‹Linguistik›. 4aArgument ‹Linguistik›. 4aKongress. 4aOslo ‹1999›. 4aSemantik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBierwisch, Manfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlutner, Reinhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorschev, Vladimir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemjjanow, Assinja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDowty, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDölling, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckardt, Regine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Thomas, econtributor.4